{
  "query": "What actions can be taken to mitigate the environmental pollution caused by waste from salmon farms?",
  "answer": "A primary action to manage waste from salmon farms involves using integrated aquaculture systems. Repairing damaged anti-predator netting around aquaculture farms is also an option, as is using acoustic devices.\n\nIntegrated aquaculture systems, while awaiting a full assessment of their effectiveness (Action 932), have shown varied results. One study in Canada indicated that blue mussels effectively absorbed waste from a salmon farm (Action 932). Another study in the USA reported increased growth in scallops placed near fish farms (Action 932). However, a related study in Spain found no evidence that oysters and mussels consumed fish farm waste (Action 932). While the overall effectiveness is unknown (Action 2774), replacing or repairing anti-predator nets can prevent further issues by reducing fish loss to predators (Action 2774). The use of acoustic devices at aquaculture systems presents a trade-off, as some studies show they reduce predation by seals on salmon, but others indicate no reduction in seal predation or impact on dolphins (Action 2775).",
